      <td><p><strong>Project Serve Proposal. A Different Approach. - Gus Row</strong></p>
        <p><strong>Background<br>
        </strong>We&rsquo;ve struggled to get people for the various projects. This may reflect a lack of buy-in to the importance of the concept (I hope that&rsquo;s not the case) or more likely, to the particular projects. </p>
        <p><strong>The Vision&hellip;. The Value</strong><br>
  I&rsquo;m absolutely convinced that the principle behind Project Serve &ndash; of finding ways to serve people and communities &ndash; is vital to our future. I think there are at least 3 ways this needs to be fostered. </p>
        <p><strong>Surge<br>
          </strong>This new flagship event for YFC is crucial. It will help establish a creative servant mentality throughout the mission. It&rsquo;s vital that we all help make it work. <br>
          <br>
          <strong>Local Community Projects<br>
        </strong>One of our practices is that we will find local projects outside of YFC to serve. We must get active in making this happen.</p>
        <p>But, in my opinion, these projects must be dangerous or at least put us on the edge. e.g. serving the local Muslim community, or the gay network. We have to put ourselves at risk, otherwise we will just be a youth version of Rotary. </p>
        <p><strong>Project Serve Overseas. </strong><br>
  This is the area I suggest we do differently. Rather than the Nationwide mission organizing projects I propose YFC areas take on a particular location/mission to serve. Some YFC areas could combine. </p>
        <p>For example (and these are only examples not suggestions of actual hook ups) </p>
        <p>Northland/Auckland could take on the work in Myanmar. <br>
  Waikato/Taranaki could take on sewa ashram in India.<br>
  South Akld/Wanganui could take on Vladivostok. <br>
  ..etc. </p>
        <p>Here&rsquo;s how it would work. A representative would go and visit and ask how can we serve you? Then they would return and begin involving their whole community in helping. Lets say the orphanage in Myanmar needed school materials.. then YFC would visit schools in Auckland and Northland with photos and info and ask them to donate resources. If Sewa Ashram needed medical supplies, Waikato/Taranaki would ask local medical centres to donate and /or visit. </p>
        <p>The goal would be to involve the non-Christians in our area, in serving the community overseas. This would build relationships all round. </p>
        <p><strong>Projects<br>
        </strong>YFC areas could consider where they&rsquo;d like to get involved and we could decide early next year. </p>
        <p>Places PS already has connection with: </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Myanmar </li>
          <li> Vladivostok </li>
          <li> Solomon Islands</li>
          <li> Fiji</li>
          <li> Samoa</li>
          <li> New Delhi </li>
          <li> ...and other centres have connections with other areas, so theres no shortage.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Note: This would not be an exclusive thing. If a person from Waikato wanted to go to Myanmar that&rsquo;s fine. But they&rsquo;d go as part of Northland/Auckland connection. </p>
        <p><strong>Long Term <br>
        </strong>The overall goal is that we&rsquo;ll develop long term servant relationships with a specific mission/village/people rather than just people from all over combining for a few trips every now and again. </p>
        <p><strong>To get there</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li> We need to buy-in to the concept </li>
          <li> We need to commit to a particular location </li>
          <li> We need to find out what would help. </li>
          <li> We need to dream crazy dreams about involving our non-Christian communities in mission &ndash; believe me, people are hungry for it. </li>
        </ul></td>
